{{Infobox ethnic group| |group= Bhadala |population = |popplace = • India • Pakistan |langs = • [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] • [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] • [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]] |rels= [[Islam]] 100% |related= • [[Mallaah]] }}
The '''Bhadala''' ({{lang-gu|ભડાલા}}; {{lang-ar|بدل}}; {{lang-hi|भदाला}}) are an [[ethnic group]] found in Pakistan and India. They are found mainly in the [[Kutch District]] of [[Gujarat]]. In [[Pakistan]], they are found mainly in [[Karachi]].<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part One edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 234 to 238</ref>
==Origin (JADEJA)== The word Bhadala meant a hardworking businessman and sea rider in the [[Kutchi language|Kutchi]] language, but now refers to a distinct community found along the coast of [[Kutch]] and [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]]. According to their traditions, they were originally settled in the town of [[Keti Bandar]] in [[Sindh]], where members of the community are still said to be found. The community were said to be invited to settle in [[Kutch]] by the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] Emperor [[Shahjahan]]. Their original settlement was the village of Mota Salaya in [[Mandvi]] [[Taluka]]. The community are now settled in a number of villages in [[Mandvi]] [[Taluka]] such as Mandis Bhadala Phool and Juna Salaya. In the 18th Century, a large number of Bhadalas moved to [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], where they settled in the ports of [[Veraval]], [[Jamnagar]], [[Dwarka|Dwaraka]] and [[Porbandar]]. A second migration took place in the 19th Century, which saw many Bhadala move to [[Mombasa]], [[Lamu]] and [[Daresalam]] in [[East Africa]]. They were pioneers in the [[Asia]]n settlement of [[East Africa]]. The community now speak Kutchi, while those in [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]] also speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]].<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part One edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 234 to 238</ref>
==Present circumstances== The Bhadala are divided into a number of clans, the main ones being the Jadeja, Sap, Aspun, Ruknani, Fatwani, Hashmani, Madwani, Kana, Babar, Bhopal, Thaim, Bholim, Turk, Madyar, Vidhani, karani, Betara, Nakhrani, Juneja, Sodha, Sameja, Patha, Palija, Koreja, Kandeja, Bhatti, Yuspani, Jafarabadi and Chauhan. Many are names of well-known [[Sindhi people|Sindhi]] tribes, and could point to a diverse origin of the community. But community boundaries are clear, and there is no intermarriage with neighbouring [[Muslim]] [[Maldhari]] communities like the [[Junejo|Juneja]], [[Royma]] and [[Ker (tribe)|Ker]]. Each of their clans are of equal status and inter marry. The community have a well established caste association, the Muslim Bhadala Jamat, which is one of the oldest Muslim castes association in [[Gujarat]]. It has offices in [[Mombasa]], [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]], [[Dubai]], [[Karachi]] (Keamari & Baba Island) and [[Keti Bandar]], reflecting the widespread distribution of the community.<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part One edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 234 to 238</ref>
The Bhadala is still a seafaring community, and almost all the [[Dhow]] captains on the [[Dubai]] to [[India]] route are Bhadala. Many are also employed by the merchant navies of [[India]] and [[Pakistan]]. Generally each [[dhow]] crew is made up of close kinsmen. In [[Pakistan]], the Bhadala owns a significant part of that countries fishing fleet. In [[India]], the Bhadala often employ [[Muslim]] [[Machiyar]] or [[Hindu]] [[Kharwa (caste)|Kharwa]] on their fishing boats, while in [[Pakistan]] most of the crew is made up of ethnic [[Bengali Muslims]].<ref>People of India Gujarat Volume XXI Part One edited by R.B Lal, P.B.S.V Padmanabham, G Krishnan & M Azeez Mohideen pages 234 to 238</ref>
The Bhadala are entirely [[Sunni]], and follow the traditions of the other neighbouring [[Muslim]] communities.
