{{Infobox language |name=South Levantine Arabic |nativename={{lang|ar|اللهجة الشامي الجنوبية}} |states=[[Jordan]], [[Israel]], [[State of Palestine|Palestine]] |speakers= 6.7 million |date=2016 |ref=e19 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] |fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]] |fam4=[[Arabic]] |fam5=[[Levantine Arabic]] |dia1=[[Jordanian Arabic]] |dia2=[[Palestinian Arabic]] |script=[[Arabic alphabet]] |lc1=ajp |notice=IPA |glotto=sout3123 |glottorefname=South Levantine Arabic |map=Levantine Arabic Map.jpg |mapcaption= {{legend|#009feb|South Levantine}} }}
'''[[South Levantine Arabic|South Levantine]]''' ({{lang-ar|اللهجة الشامي الجنوبية}}), a subdivision of [[Levantine Arabic]], is spoken in [[State of Palestine|Palestine]], as well as in the western area of [[Jordan]] (in the ‘[[Ajloun Governorate|Ajlun]], [[Balqa Governorate|Al Balqa’]], [[Karak Governorate|Al Karak]], [[Mafraq Governorate|Al Mafraq]], [[Amman Governorate|‘Amman]], [[Irbid Governorate|Irbid]], [[Jerash Governorate|Jarash]], and [[Madaba Governorate|Madaba]] governorates).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/map/JOSY|title=Jordan and Syria|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-21|language=en}}</ref> The language is also spoken in the [[Northern District (Israel)|HaZafon district]] of Israel,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/ajp|title=Arabic, South Levantine Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref> south of [[Lebanon]].
== See also == * [[Varieties of Arabic]] * [[Levantine Arabic]] * [[Jordanian Arabic]] * [[Palestinian Arabic]]
== Literature == Some parts of the Bible have been published in South Levantine Arabic. The [[British and Foreign Bible Society]] published the Gospel of Mark in 1940, and in 1946 the Gospel of Matthew and the Letter of James which were in Arabic script.
